history.prompt: Explain why the sky is blue
history.response:
Hey there! Oh yeah, the sky looks pretty blue today huh? That's actually pretty chill question - no need to stress about it though! 

So yeah, basically the sky appears blue because of something called Rayleigh scattering. It's basically how light interacts with our atmosphere. When sunlight hits those tiny molecules in the air, they scatter shorter blue wavelengths more than longer ones - kinda like how ocean waves scatter blue water waves better than red ones. That's why we see blue instead of violet (which would technically be there if we could see it). Pretty neat how science works itself out naturally, right?

Not exactly rocket science though - just one of those little quirks of physics doing its thing. No big deal either way!
